<br>
I don't mind suggestions, for the most part. But if I'm in a group and running high mana and no ones dying I don't need instruction. It might get a bit close for some's comfort but if you are near full health after a multiple pull I dont need someone's instruction on how to cleric. If, on a nasty pull, by the time i stand up the tank is at two bubbles i will start to rapid heal them with remedy and celestials to pad them with enough hit points for the complete heal. I don't need someone telling me that i should be using other healing spells.<br>
<br>
Then again if I am new to a zone and someone dies from my lack of experience( including getting myself killed from over healing agro) my ears are open to new techniques.<br>
<br>
And to finish I must mention something about Lay on Hands. This is something you see less of as you progress in levels but it still happens every once in awhile. If a battle is coming down to the wire and its time to start figuring out who lives and who dies I will ask the paladin if LoH is up, and if it is to get ready to use it on him/her-self or the tank(if they are not tanking). If I know its up i will focus my heals on other soon to be dead groupmembers(after alerting the paladin of this). At this point if the paladin flubs their LoH by using it on the critter we are in battle with and they die I don't need other groupmembers asking me why i didnt heal the paladin. And kudos to the paladins who step up and admit they screwed up their LoH and rude to those who stay quiet about it. Mistakes certainly happen but its the admittance of those mistakes that make for great players.<br>
<br>
<br>
Quinnaros Fascia<br>
Vicar of the Prime Healer<br>
